The Saltglass Reach is the eastern transit corridor from the inland desert basin to the coast, terminating at Mafdet's harbor. Four terrain bands run west to east: Mirror Flats (hard salt crust — the evaporation basin of the vanished Iseth Reach river — blinding by day, reflective at night; caravans cross at dawn and dusk), Glasswind Belts (fields of wind-cut silica shards created when the Ninth Meridian's thermal pulse fused surface sand into glass; glass color guides navigation — milky for stable ground, amber for thermal fault proximity, violet for eclipse-rite residue), Tariff Cairn Lines (three parallel chains of engineered survey markers once certifying cargo transition from inland caravan law to maritime levy law; swift line for light/high-value cargo, heavy road for bulk commodities, sealed route for funerary and quarantined consignments), and Tidemouth Dunes (brackish channels marking approach to the coast, where the Shoreward Seal — a large basalt slab carved with both inland charter notation and maritime loading symbols — marked the legal threshold between jurisdictions). The Shoreward Conversion was the Reach's defining institutional innovation: cargo, contracts, and legal obligations were translated from inland water-law standards to maritime risk-assessment at this boundary, requiring Shoreward Assessors trained in both legal traditions. Their Shoreward Tables are the direct ancestors of Mafdet's Saltweight standard. The Littoral Branch of Measure Script — developed by Keeper-era coastal scribes adapting the inland Measure Script for maritime use — survived the Keepers' collapse and became the basis of Mafdet's Ledger House notation. Current state: one primary track following the former Heavy Road alignment plus informal whisper routes through the Glasswind Belts used by smugglers and Synod couriers.

