Kethari hydrological memory of the Saltglass Reach centers on the Mirror Flats: the evaporation basin of the Iseth Reach river, whose drying created the salt crust visible today.
The Mirror Flats are the visible record of a catastrophic hydrology failure — the landscape remembers the water through the mineral deposits it left behind; the salt crust's depth records the river's terminal phase with geological precision.
The Glasswind Belts' glass formation from the Ninth Meridian thermal pulse is a separate geological event overprinting the same landscape: two distinct catastrophes in the same terrain, the earlier (hydrology failure) beneath and the later (thermal event) on top.
Kethari geological consultants to caravan operations use this layered record to explain why Reach navigation requires understanding both surface glass behavior and subsurface salt stability — the two hazard systems operate on different timescales and respond differently to load, temperature, and moisture.

