Khephari geological analysis of the Saltglass Reach focuses on the Glasswind Belt composition as a forensic record of the Ninth Meridian catastrophe's thermal pulse.
The glass color gradient — milky for pre-catastrophe sand, amber near thermal fault proximity, violet where eclipse-rite residue altered sand chemistry — is readable as a heat-intensity map of the pulse propagation across the Reach.
The spatial distribution of violet glass corresponds to the predicted spread pattern of the rite's energy discharge through the dry Iseth channel system; amber zones mark where the heat pulse encountered subsurface mineral pockets that concentrated thermal energy.
This distribution tells a Khephari analyst that the Ninth Meridian rite's energy release was not uniform but channeled by existing dry-channel topography — the same channels that once carried the Iseth Reach's water carried the rite's thermal pulse eastward.
The glass is not merely a hazard indicator but a geological record of the event that can be read by trained eyes to reconstruct the pulse's path and intensity distribution.
